Inflation in Europe has slipped on food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
In November, the price increase in the 13 euro area countries was higher than expected, after an inflation rate of 2.6% in October, annual inflation of 3.1% was recorded, said the European Community Bureau of Statistics located in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts indicated only 3 per cent, Bloomberg said.
Unlike the US, British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the interest rate by saying that declining interest rates, with growth in commodity prices and falling unemployment rates, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two per cent.
According to an analyst, Catch 22 for the ECB is "we must deterre" inflation so that we no longer have to intervene on this subject at a later stage.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 per cent is a record in the last 12 years and in Spain it rose from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area took off as a result of the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
The market term of the cereal ratings have increased by 88 per cent and the price of soya has also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of edible oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the world price of oil rose by 52 per cent, and last month a barrel of black gold was worth almost 100 dollars.
According to the ECB, in 2008 the inflation rate will rise from 2.1 this year to 2.5 per cent, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3%, however, the average annual rate will be 2.1% over the next 3 to 4 months.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to lower the policy rate twice in 2008.
