Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by almost twenty percent
The hypermarkets in the commercial triangle in Budaers maintained the average price increase of 16 per cent last year, the difference that this year's VAT rate did not go up.
Article by Napi Gazdasag (daily economy)
This year, in the Budaers trading triangle, the usual daily Christmas basket also increased by an average of 16 percent, a much higher value increase to a thousand forints was displayed in all hypermarkets.
Prices, which had already soared in the department stores last December, did not rise sharply compared to the previous high base.
Nevertheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that the items purchased well below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand Hints.
The daily basket in the hypermarkets surveyed exceeded the psychological threshold of a total of 10 thousand forints by at least 91 forints.
And the highest value in the basket was 10,273 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 forints.)
Prices for Unicum and live fish remained almost at the level of last year, however, turkey, nut and poppy prices rose sharply.
In shops, the price of flour and bread followed data from the KSH (Central Statistics Institute), but at Auchan's only bread was found from 1 kg to 139 heints.
Competition did not lower the product price below 200 forints.
It was astonishing to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the two-litre Coca-Cola bottle was below 200 forints, so it only cost 257 Vints the recorded bottle included.
It only preempts this year, in terms of daily basket, Auchan was the most expensive and cheapest Cora.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of its daily basket by 15 per cent, while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 and 18 per cent respectively.
Comparing the most expensive basket of last year and the cheapest basket of this year, we see a gap of 12 percent while the difference between last year's cheapest and most expensive this year is 21 percent.
Prices increased by HUF 1,480 on average.
Last year, prices rose by HUF 1 206 on average, while knowing that the impact of the increase in the VAT rate was already noticed in last year's Christmas prices.
This process has perplexed trade, hypermarkets could not visibly determine which margin to apply to products as they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the rotation of a product, he risks losing a large profit on the margin adjusted to the intensity of trade.)
As a result of the change in the VAT rate, the increase in daily basket prices has changed in such an assume so excessive that the most expensive basket was 1 720 forints higher than the value of 2006 whereas the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive since the value of the most expensive basket was 1,630 forints higher than last year's, and the cheapest prices also increased by 1,284 forints.
By bringing the two seasons closer to Christmas, we have seen a catastrophic increase in prices, in less than 20 months the prices of everyday consumer goods have risen by more than 30 per cent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH data: for some foods of primary necessity, the Institute of Statistics has found a price increase of more than 30 per cent in 12 months.
