However, according to our information, turnover is lower in the provinces, and many multinationals are complaining to the fact that they are not even up to the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer goods.
Many hospitals save on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by the incorrect use of antibiotics, have been recorded in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overwork of medical personnel do not help to block infections, says the chief doctor of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals also save on disinfectants
Not long ago, an MRSA infection was diagnosed at the trauma department of the Junos Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was detected in a man hospitalized as a result of a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured person in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital but not until recently had returned due to an MRSA infection and since then the doctors have not been able to do a major operation because of the bacterium in his body.
As of December 10 this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multidrug-resistant pathogen were reported to the National System of Civil Surveillance, said Karolina Bocz, chief physician of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
Namely, it's the number of infections caused by a multi-resistant pathogen that has actually been recorded in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. by staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
One third of people carry the Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium in their noses without developing a disease.
Infections caused by AS (such as angina, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, and are easily curable.
However, if antibiotics are used in excessive or inappropriate ways, the bacterium, which reacts well to antibiotics, will develop a well-resistant bacterium that will proliferate rapidly in poor hospital conditions.
In the event of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium can cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or sepsis, on elderly patients, low weight or with a weakened organism.
According to the doctor head of the Jonos Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily life of hospitals.
Above all, infection should not be confused with the epidemic, there is no MRSA just it or we are not looking for it, said Tibor Nyulasi.
ASs are resistant to antibiotics.
'These patients are isolated, the caregiver puts rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics adapted to treat them,' said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, inpatient patients are examined if they are carriers of MRSA, however infection cannot always be avoided.
The sample sample is not in fashion
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current conditions and circumstances are not favourable in Hungarian hospitals to prevent the development and proliferation of multidrug-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Borcz.
As this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and residences for the elderly, hospitals should monitor in-patients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not finance these examinations.
Most cases are only found if the MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the chief physician of the epidemiological centre.
The European Union has rigorous recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are Hungarian directives also for the cure of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological examinations should be carried out in order to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take it into account.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in outpatient care and basic care, said Karolina Boercz.
Many hospitals save on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that the MRSA proliferate of one patient has another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, to put on gloves and protective masks. However, there are significant shortcomings in hospitals also in this area.
MRSA proliferate by infection transmitted by droplets and contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
Moreover, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other, while in terms of the epidemic, the sick should be kept apart by a minimum of 1.5 metres.
Unfortunately, we also see that hospitals, which are in a difficult financial situation, are saving on disinfectants, they lack nurses, the patients are numerous, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Boruzcz.
According to Karolina Borzcz, in hospitals where preventive measures are followed, the number of infections is lower in demonstrable manner or the proliferation of the pathogenic agent may be blocked.
Government project against the MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection represents exorbitant expenses for social security funds, which is why this infection is being combated everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a programme to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSAs.
According to published data, this programme is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) identifies among its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multi-drug resistant pathogens (such as MRSAs) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
