Additional EUR 400 million for infrastructure
The Hungarian Minister of Finance, J. Veres, and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three agreements on a total value of EUR 400 million on a credit line on Budapest to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure and energy efficiency.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for Hungarian budget financing of transport and environment projects to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund, of which a credit agreement worth EUR 100 million has already been signed by the parties. This time, the contract signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million credit agreement also concerns the budgetary financing of projects linked to education.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary, with the remaining EUR 150 million available for later, following the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties have signed a EUR 50 million contract for innovation, the state budget will use this envelope primarily as part of the research and development project to be carried out at the University of Debrecen.
During the negotiations, the metro line 4 project was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would discuss the possible amendment of the original contract once Hungary has finalised the details of the metro financing with the EU.
According to Jonos Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has provided a total of EUR 8.4 billion for the financing of 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB provides its loans at the interest rate linked to EURIBOR, with a grace period of 8 years and without a commitment fee.
Bulgaria, an EU Real Estate Market
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, with the attention of the whole of Europe being focused on this Balkan country little mentioned in the past.
What, or who buys in this EU market which is still the cheapest but will quickly become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
Currently, in real estate, Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most popular target in Eastern Europe with its ski apartments and cheap seaside houses.
In the mountains, the most popular regions are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albéna, the "Golden Sands", the "Sun Coast", the former Sozopol and Nessebar but more and more are looking for a building in the Kavarna and Balcik region as well.
According to analysts at Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later, the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also arouse investors' interest, and there are also more and more of them to buy in the cheap corner of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital, offers attractive opportunities as well, the areas of shops and offices promise the highest depreciation rate.
Bulgaria is on the best route to become one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe and thus to be a priority destination, after the summer season and the winter season, also in the other two seasons of the year.
More vigilant investors are already buying in large numbers, for example in the corner of Bansko.
According to analysts, people buying a building in Bulgaria are still looking for a change in their lives, their way of life.
Most buyers are English but others are from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. On the Black Sea and in the most famous ski resorts, we traditionally meet many Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who intend to move to settle buy renovated buildings, have a price ranging from 50 to 100 thousand euros, or old dilapidated houses, has a price ranging from 5 to 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication opportunities, proximity to a large city, shops and, in general, the local doctor.
The second group includes second-hand home buyers (since last December, Bulgaria is one of the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group is made up of commercial investors who buy in the hope of achieving medium or long-term capital gains.
The price of buildings in the capital is constantly increasing as a result of growing demand.
In the European Union, house prices are the lowest in Bulgaria. However, over the past 5 years, they have increased by 21 per cent each year.
The increase in house prices mainly exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the Hungarian six per cent
According to the communication by the Minister for the Environment and Waters, the Minister for the Environment and Waters, meetings of professionals are being completed on Tuesday, however, on Wednesday, after the official opening, the ministers' negotiations on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Road Map that is expected to define efforts to achieve the Kyoto Protocol emission reduction period until 2012.
At the moment, there is a great deal of discussion between developing and developed countries.
The United States also reported that, for the time being, it did not wish to discuss exact figures, while it was ready to sign an agreement on the reduction, until 2020, of greenhouse gas emissions from 25 to 40 per cent from the 1990 level.
Another important topic of the conference was whether developed countries were committing themselves, excluding emission reductions, to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement has also been signed on aid to developing countries.
The aid fund defined by the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a 16-member Governing Council probably under the United Nations Global Environment Facility (GEF), said Piac és Profit (Market and Profit).
The six per cent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister for the Environment and Waters, Gobor Fodor, confirms the EU's ambition to retain its role as flagship in overall efforts to protect the climate and to encourage the signing of the new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU was committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 20% compared to 1990 levels, regardless of the successful signing of the "Agreements 2012", and it was expected to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by up to 30 per cent if the other major regions of the world and/or developing countries were also responsible for making commitments to their responsibility and capabilities.
Mr Fodor recalled that in 1997 the Kyoto Protocol countries had a total reduction of 5.2 per cent and all 15 EU members of that time committed an additional 8 per cent.
Hungary is committed to reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent from the level of the period between 1985 and 1987, and our country will fulfil its commitment, recalls the press release of the Minister for the Environment.
The stakes are high in Bali because the long-term international agreement on climate policy must be put in place within two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be postponed until 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments below the values provided for in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international emission reduction system, the need for which was stressed in the new report of IPCC, the international scientific body, which won the Nobel Peace Prize for Climate Change.
The reduction in emissions would be delayed and the increase in the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2 degrees Celcius could no longer be avoided which, according to the scientists, would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
British Army Recruits on YouTube
British Army units communicate on the video-sharing site recordings made during its operations in Iraq and Afghanistan in order to make themselves popular.
First, it is the British Air Force (BYR) that has been passionate about YouTube: special units in Afghanistan are charging video footage on operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC announced.
These recordings, taken with the help of miniature cameras mounted on the helmets, are checked at the Kandahar Air Force Operations headquarters and are then transferred to London where the compatriots charge them over the Internet.
The political message is inescapable
Air force soldiers have already passed 139 footage through this route and their "chain" has been watched by more than 75,000 people.
The British Defence Department registered as "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 and reports videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan as the Commonwealth Minister (Commonwealth Office) and the international peacekeeping forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own channels on YouTube.
Mission to Afghanistan
According to the original purpose of the air force, the videos were made on the net to recruit. According to the Ministry of Defence, they also served to make the general public aware of the real objectives of the presence of the army abroad.
Propaganda published by this route bears virtually nothing compared to the usual recruitment advertisements that have been made on television, the BBC Gordon Mackenzie, a defence consultant, told the BBC. On the other hand, it also inevitably carries a political message, since it justifies in a special form the validity of the military operations decided by the Government.
Americans have made a game
The army is empathised because, apart from the carefully composed and censored videos, amateur videos are sent to the sharing site that also present, for example, the death of soldiers: in the “official” propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers do not avoid talking about the losses but they never present the bloody side of the fight.
Indeed, many videos were already posted on the net showing the areas of operation in Iraq and Afghanistan that were being carried out on a real mission, but the British army is only rushing to load these videos for a recent time.
Americans do the recruitment a little bit differently using the American's Army shooting game that can be downloaded free of charge. In this game, the player can put himself directly in the place of soldiers in a more or less real simulation.
