A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which trace the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are in free access.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of linear in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were previously available only for “humanitarian” purposes, i.e. individually and nominatively, at the request of a former victim or his or her successors in title.
The eleven States in charge of their management - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
With the completion of the ratification of this agreement by all States, the opening has been in place since yesterday.
Sensitive information
Access by historians to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to conduct research “including the movement of prisoners, the camp population and the state of health of the forced labourers”, explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, opposed the opening of these nominative documents to the public, because of the sensitivity of certain information.
Like the supposed homosexuality or mental disability of some victims of deportation.
The registers of the concentration camps or arrest warrants prepared by the Gestapo had been collected after the war for practical purposes: to locate civilians who were deported or subjected to compulsory work and, possibly, to provide them with proof of their internment, in order to open the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees are processing tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
“There is nothing fundamentally new to waiting for from these documents,” said Professor Wolfgang Benz, Director of the Anti-Semitism Research Centre at the Technische University in Berlin in 2006.
