What insurance is right for me?
Motor insurance, which covers the driver in the face of possible claims, involves a large expense which will depend on various factors, such as age, sex, length of life of the driving licence, civil status, type of vehicle to be insured or use, among others.
Having a car is the main one.
There is only, escoger el seguro de autom-vil adecuado es inclusiveo m-s dif-cil que elegir el modelo de veh-culo.
And that's that, choosing the right car insurance, is even harder than choosing the model of the vehicle.
Car insurance is an agreement between an insurance company and the insurer.
This compromise is embodied in an insurance contract, which establishes that the company receives the value of the premium granted and in exchange it becomes responsible for the obligation to pay compensation in the event of a claim.
The premium is the price of insurance, which is based on various factors, such as age, sex, seniority of the driving licence, civil status, type of vehicle to be insured or the use that is made, inter alia.
Insurance companies set their prices on the basis of statistics, so that the higher the probability of an accident, the higher the rating to be paid.
It is for this reason that people over the age of 25 and women have to pay lower premiums, since statistics show that these people have a lower rate of claims due to their prudence.
Similarly, using censuses, companies have concluded that married persons tend to have fewer accidents than single drivers.
The use of the vehicle will influence the frequency, and therefore the probability of having an accident.
By increasing the frequency, the probabilities increase.
There are many variables that insurers take into account when establishing the price of the premium.
For this reason, the driver must study the situation carefully in order to choose the motor insurance that best fits his profile.
We will present here the most significant variables when choosing one or the other type of insurance, so that insurance, in addition to adapting to the characteristics of the insurer, offers it a reasonable price.
Young people under the age of 25 face various disadvantages when entering into an insurance contract at an affordable price, such as the low experience in driving and long-term driving licences.
Although the ideal way to be well insured is insurance at risk, other more cost-effective options exist.
The most far-sighted drivers can opt for insurance at risk with deductible, so that they obtain insurance coverage at any risk but at a more accessible price.
This form of agreement implies that the customer pays part of the amount of the claim.
"The part of the amount of the claim that the customer pays will be established on the basis of the value of the premium, which will be higher, the lower the amount," says Luis Noguera, Spain's manager of First Europa, online insurance mediator.
Another option is third-party insurance extended, so that the customer provides protection to deal with damage caused to third parties, but by damage caused on his own car.
In addition, it would be covered against theft, fire and vehicle loss.
One piece of advice.
If you are a 25-year-old trying to be careful and avoid claims as much as possible, as long as it will affect the bonus, which may reduce the price of insurance in the future.
A subsidy is a reduction in the base rate that the company owns.
On the contrary, a sanction is a mark-up of the basic tariff.
"The bonuses and sanctions will depend on the company and the benefit of the company.
If the company has had a good year, it will be able to afford to increase the bonuses", Claren Noguera.
Beyond the age of 25, it becomes easier for drivers when they place an insurance contract, since the rate of claims is reduced by the experience accumulated.
It is for this reason that it is preferable to choose any risk insurance with a deductible basis.
'Nourle young people cannot benefit from the experience beforehand after an accident,' says the director of the European company in Spain and adds that the majority of accidents occur during the second year of driving, once the 'fear of the novice' has passed.
However, if the client is married but does not yet have children, it is preferable for him to negotiate insurance at risk, however long his economic situation allows him to do so.
Marriages with children are considered by insurers to be the persons with the lowest level of claims, because the increases will be lower.
In this case, the best insurance would be insurance at any risk with deductible (which may be EUR 300), or third-party insurance extended from the third year of life of the vehicle when the insured person has a high level of bonus.
"They have a more relaxed conduct and they have greater purchasing power to afford the luxury of assuming a larger amount of franchises," Luis Noguera said.
For pensioners, insurance at any risk with deductible is preferable (with a maximum of EUR 150), or an extended third-party anity when the insurer has a high level of bonuses.
It must be said that motor insurance is something important, not only because it covers the driver in the face of possible disasters, but also because it represents a large expense, which is why it is essential to study properly the insurance that suits us most according to our personal circumstances.
