Venus is the earth's infernal twin.
Despite its hostile atmosphere, Venus looks more like Earth than previously believed: the European space probe 'Venus Express' has discovered flashes in the atmosphere and wind eddies at the poles, as similar to those that appear in winter on Earth.
For almost three decades, scientists have been assuming that there are flashes of Venus.
The European 'Venus Express' probe has today proved this - it has detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: the flashes on Venus burst at a height of about 56 kilometers of cloud cloud, says Christopher Russell from the University of California to Los Angeles in the scientific magazine 'Nature'.
According to the famous theory of cyprine, lightning revealed life on Earth: the storm stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
This is not the case on Venus: "If there has been life, it must have been on a very ancient date in history," says Sean Solomon of the Carbonist Institution in Washington.
There should be little living things on the surface of Venus today: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, there are temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus may be the Earth's infernal twin, but she remains a twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which looks so much like the Earth in mass and dimensions, was struck by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ESA mission.
The departure of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was an important step in Venusian research, as no more probes had been on the way to explore this planet since the 1990s.
In the view of the researchers, the most recent research results that have now been presented in several articles in "Nature" do not only highlight the singularity of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the commonalities with the Earth of our neighboring planet are more numerous than at first glance.
For example, in addition to the vortices of wind already known at the north pole, found a vortex of clouds at the south pole, which rotates even faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of draughts in the Earth's hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, almost as large.
The so-called evening or morning star germinated revolves around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it turns much more slowly on itself: a Venusian day lasts 243 days of land.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, hardly recalls the Earth, scientists assume that the two planets formed under similar conditions.
Of both, water accumulated and remained on Earth as oceans, but was lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has bonded to Earth as carbonate, it forms most of the atmosphere on Venus.
