At the moment, wooden boxes made in Sweden cast shadows on Warhol's list of works.
Many of the ninety Brillo-Boxes of "Type Stockholm" listed there are counter-facies.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned a few months ago the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo-Boxes, the internal research of the Moderna Museet in Stockholm today leads to a disenchanting result: the six "Brillo-Boxes", which the former director of the Pontus Hulten Museum gave a gift in 1995 to the Moderna Museet,which circulate on the international art market.
The ancient history is entangled, a disconcerting sequence of artistic and curatorical productions.
In 1964, Warhol created in New York's first "Brillo-Boxes", painted wooden boxes, which are based on the red-blue-white design of "Brillo" powder soap cartons.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet featured in 1968 - with the Warhol's agreement - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: Warhol did not come (for financial reasons) but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but rather their models, exposure samples.
At the same time, Warhol had made it clear in 1968 that a few Brillo wooden boxes would be produced in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time today speak of about fifteen wooden boxes which at the time would have entered law into the history of art and auctions, as original Brillo-Boxes of authorized Andy Wahrol, with the name "Type Stockholm".
Some of them reached more than USD 100,000 in auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén Museum mistakenly claimed that about 100 wooden boxes had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol would later have given over to him.
In fact, Hultén's 105 coffers were produced in Malmo in 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time, Warhol had already died for three years.
Lars Bystrom, the chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined, next to the museum's six Brillo-Boxes, three more of Swedish private collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminated panels were first printed and sanded, then a white oil paint brush was applied.
The texture of the copies dating from 1990 reveals, on the contrary, that the paint was applied directly without a background layer to the laminated panels, using a roll of paint - moreover, it is not an oil paint, but an acrylic.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes", let the director of the Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve, hear: 'If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come yet another decision, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection.
Already in July the Authentication Board has, of course, announced that it would investigate the "heavy charges" that will be raised in the case of boxes of powder soap.
